Hi, i tried it with the new link.
i switched my linebreak now to the suggested " \r\n" and it seems to work now (at least in Firefox). Internet Explorer shows me a linebreak in the console, but when the excel is generated i can see only a space character and no line break ??

I experienced also one non IE javascript line in the exceljs source
line 3351 ->     } else if (reference.startsWith('#')) {

i have to replace it with 

    } else if (reference.startsWith('#')) {

otherwise my IE will get an exception

@MartinKolarik https://github.com/npm/registry/issues/174

@Mafi78 Which version IE?

Almost seems like this needs to find and replace newlines to `\r\n` on setting values (so it's correct when saved and when re-reading it stays consistent). An alternative would be transparent set/get so internally it's `\r\n` but all reading / writing uses plain `\n` (I always have to check the correct order because I don't do it often - and I can't be the only one).

@Rycochet: IT is IE 11.0.9600 (on Windows 7) it is the actual version available (at least when you trust Windows Update)

I don't get your last comment ? should i update my string with \n\r instead of \r\n ?? I am sorry :)
I've also read that a special setting (i think it was a style of the worksheet itself) was necessary - should i try that out ?

@Rycochet: as in issue 296 described (https://github.com/guyonroche/exceljs/issues/296) i tried to set the style of the workbook. 

But i am not using a WorkbookWriter ?
 I instantiate a new Workbook Object and don'T know how to set the correct attribute
that.workbook = new Excel.Workbook();

Putting `\r\n` in is correct - I'm just wondering if ExcelJS should automatically handle it so it's not needed (MS does seem to love `\r\n` even if nobody else does :-P )

I did read elsewhere that there is a flag related to multi-line, but I honestly can't remember what it is (check the other issues maybe?), or what it does.

Hopefully someone gets the time to look at that specific error on IE - though it's most likely the use of `string.startsWith()` which isn't supported on IE at all, and needs either polyfill or a simple workaround -

```javascript
function startsWith(str, prefix, position) {
   if (str.startsWith) {
      return str.startsWith(prefix, position);
   }
   return str.substr(position || 0, prefix.length) === prefix;
}
```

Another thing that IE does not love is an assignment of an object with 
This syntax. I also saw it in the exceljs.js file
/*var worksheetOptions = Object.assign({}, options, {
      id: id,
      name: name,
      workbook: this
    });*/

i had to change it to this 
    var worksheetOptions = {
      id: id,
      name: name,
      workbook: this
    };

then i was able to use exceljs in IE :) 
IE javascript behaviour and the rest of the world is really nasty - so much work to do twice. Not good.

I made some more tests ... and thought i found my solution by replacing my &lt;br&gt; in html with " \n" but i did not make an difference ...
